ceased","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","10 February 1370":"10 February 1370","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":113,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen was born in 1342, in England. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Roger Brereton."},"et":{"1342–":"1342–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1342–Female":"1342–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","10 February 1370":"10. veebruar 1370","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1342–":"1342–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1342–Female":"1342–Kuollut","about 1370":"noin 1370","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","10 February 1370":"10. helmikuuta 1370","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1342–":"1342–Décédée","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1342–Female":"1342–Décédée","about 1370":"environ 1370","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","10 February 1370":"10 février 1370","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Ellen est née en 1342, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Roger Brereton."},"de":{"1342–":"1342–Verstorben","1340–Male":"1340–Verstorben","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1370–Male":"1370–Verstorben","1342–Female":"1342–Verstorben","about 1370":"um 1370","1455":"1455","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","10 February 1370":"10. Februar 1370","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Ellen wurde 13